The athletic Maronite, richly and gayly attired, with broad, flat turban and scarlet vest, strode away with a confident bearing, while his fair and comely wife bent her head as she emerged from the door-way whose height scarcely afforded space for her tall tantour;

The tantour is a horn of silver, or some inferior metal, which the married women of the Lebanon, both Maronites and Druses, wear on the head. It is nearly a foot and a half in height, is sometimes richly embossed, and over it is thrown a long, white veil, thus imparting to the wearer a singular, but not ungraceful appearance.
                   the self-absorbed and dignified Turk passed on without looking to right or left; and here and there a stern Druse, with his hand on his heavy scimitar, folded his mantle over his bronzed visage and came stealthily out amidst the crowd.

"Ah," replied the peasant-woman, following them with a wistful gaze as they turned into the path leading to the foot of the mountain gorge, "labor is the lot of Yoosoof's helpmeet, and her shadow will be long in coming;

The Syrian peasants reckon time by their shadows, and the coming of the shadow signifies nightfall.
                   but sunshine and joy to the Lebanon Rose, and long life to the Frank."
